page.title: 19Rural - Woodland
page.content: Although the rural area within this square is predominantly high quality agricultural land there are also a few sections of woodland. The woodland is in two large areas in the north west of the square. These consist of a mixture of coniferous and deciduous (mainly Birch, Elm, Ash & Sycamore) trees which were originally planted by the Wemyss Estate. These trees therefore, belong to the Laird of Wemyss and the only body who can officially order the felling of trees is the Wemyss Estate. There are quite a few elm trees throughout this square but luckily, so far, very few have had to be felled as a result of Dutch Elm Disease. The small wooded areas on the outskirts of the villages provide well used recreational areas for both the elderly and the young.
